Some incidents you investigate may deal with contraband images, stolen data, or unlawful access to data. You’ll have to determine whether the user had knowledge of the file(s) in question, or whether the file(s) existed on the user’s system. 

The following study material will assist you to determine the following:  Did the user log into the student profile (Drone101E-book.pdf), and/or moved the file to a USB? 

In order to reach an understanding, you’d need to piece together the following information : 

- Was there a USB device connected to the system? (Registry) 
    
- Did the user navigate to the USB device? (Shell Bags) 
    
- Was a file moved to the USB device? (Time Stamps with .lnk files) 
    

- Was the file opened on the USB device? (File Opening/Registry)

Understanding USB/attached devices 

There are several security risks associated with a USB device. There are small, portable, high-capacity storage devices that can be used to exfiltrate data from an organization, or they can be used to deliver malware to an organization to compromise its security protocols. As a digital forensic investigator, you will want to know whether there was any USB devices attached to the host that you are examining. We will discuss some Windows system artifacts that will allow you to identify USB device usage on the host. We will now look at the results for registry keys. The first key can be found at the following path: 

SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Enum\USB 

This registry key identifies the USB devices attached to the system, as shown in the following output: 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Content of Registry key - SYSTEM\CurrentControlSet\Enum\USB 

We can see there were USB devices attached to the system. Devices that do NOT have a unique volume serial number will have an & as the second character of the volume serial number. In the MountedDevices key in the SYSTEM hive, which can be found in SYSTEM\MountedDevices, we can map the USB device(s) via the serial number to a drive letter on the system: 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Content of Registry key - SYSTEM\MountedDevices 

Whenever data is analyzed, we can see the USB serial numbers that were connected to the system. One was recognized as the E: drive.  This example contains an error and doesn’t show it.  The serial number and GUID will be there during normal operations. The question still remains as to which user account was responsible for the USB device usage? To determine the answer to that question, we would have to take the GUID from each of the USB devices and compare them to the user’s NTUSER.DAT file.  

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Content of Registry key - Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\MountPoints2 

As you can see, the GUIDs in the registry entry, which shows when the devices were last mounted. So we can now say that the user used a specific USB device on the system while the student account was logged in.  The correct GUID is 6d781ed1-f08d-4113-82bb-9d4c3a714575 

Shell Bags & Folder MRU 

Shellbags are a set of registry keys that remember the size and location of the folders and libraries that the user has accessed via the GUI. In addition, you may find artifacts showing user interaction with network devices, removable media, or encrypted containers. You will find them in a registry hive called USRCLASS.DAT, located in the users, AppData\Local\Microsoft\Windows folder. Most commercial forensic tools will parse out the shellbags from the USRCLASS.DAT file, but the presentation of the artifact will be different. I like to use Eric Zimmerman’s Shellbag Explorer as an open-source alternative. 

In the following screenshot, you can see the graphical representation of the folders the user accessed via the Windows GUI. This screenshot is taken from Shellbag Explorer: 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

On this diagram we can see that that the user logged into the student profile navigated to E:\USB_Exfil 

Time Stamps: 

A .lnk file is used by the Windows operating system as a shortcut and/or link to files, applications, and resources. It’s a simple, easy-to-use method for users to gain access to frequently used documents or applications. The link file will contain useful information for the digital forensic investigator, including the following: 

- File MAC times 
    
- File size 
    

- File path 
    
- Volume details 
    

This digital footprint will remain even if the destination file has been deleted. The system will create a link file every time the file is double-clicked or when using the File Open dialog box. These types of link files will be stored in the Recent folder located at the following path: <PROFILE>\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Recent 

Whenever it's deemed necessary to acquire timestamps of files,  we will look at .lnk file shortcuts which is evidence of file opening. These are files that populate recent documents in Windows. Most commercial forensics tools parse these files easily. Depending on the version, the history file will be in the following areas:

Most Recently Used 

An MRU (Most Recently Used) is a list of recently used files stored in the user’s NTUSER.DAT hive. When you open an application and see the history list of prior files that the application has used, you are looking at an MRU. There are a lot of MRU lists stored within the registry file. We will go over some more common locations. When exploring the extracted hive use Eric Zimmermans Registry Explorer. 

NTUSER.DAT\Software\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\RecentDocs 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\RecentDocs\.pdf 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

SOFTWARE\Microsoft\Windows\CurrentVersion\Explorer\RecentDocs\Folder 

Entries of potential interest include also OneDrive and CloudLog. If I am looking for evidence of specific files, the subject may store the data in cloud storage. When I see artifacts showing the use of cloud storage, it provides additional locations that I will have to locate and acquire the digital evidence to continue my digital forensic investigation. 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

Jump Lists 

JumpLists were introduced with Windows 7 and are very similar to the Recent folder are LNK files). They allow the user to access frequently used/recently used files from the Windows taskbar. Even if the user clears out the Recent folder, it will not clear out the information stored in the JumpLists. 

JumpLists can be found at the following paths: 

- %UserProfile%\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Recent\Automaticdesti nations 
    
- %UserProfile%\AppData\Roaming\Microsoft\Windows\Recent\CustomDestinations 
    

There are two types of JumpLists: 

- Automatic – system-created. Records information about file usage. 
    
- Custom – application-created. Records task-specific information about the application. 
    

In the following screenshot, you can see the AutomaticDestinations folder, and inside the folder will be files containing the JumpLists: 

![](data:image/png;base64,) 

From this we can see that Microsoft Edge opened up the Drone10 1E-book.pdf after the user clicked on the file located on the E: drive. Many applications can open up .pdf files. 

Summary 

We have enough information to show the student inserted a USB drive, copied the .pdf to the drive and opened it. There are many overlapping artifacts in Windows to prove file access and knowledge.  Please read the source material at the start of this document for more Windows forensic artifacts to help you prove what an individual did after they gained access to the box.
